segments.text: If you will, if you'll tell me your full name, for starters, and a little about... My name is Alec, A-L-E-C, Christopher Sears.
And where you were born and raised?
Born in September 7, 1918, in Abilene, Texas, and grew up in
a town west of there called Merkle, 17 miles.
I went to high school and graduated there.
I spent two years in McMurray and Abilene.
Then I went to Texas Tech, Lubbock, for a degree in agriculture.
animal husbandry, minor in economics.
The succeeding year, I had a graduate fellowship to the University of North Dakota at Fargo to work, to teach, and
I'm going up to Bismarck in June.
I'm giving a talk on the grasslands.
I enjoyed my years up there.
Anyway, I taught half time, went to school half time, and earned a master's in animal husbandry and a minor in economics.
kind of taking off on the education part here.
I'll go back and pick up my early life.
While we're on it, I might as well finish.
While in North Dakota, my research project dealt with vermifuges and parasites in sheep, and I worked closely with
the veterinary division there in the school.
I became very interested in veterinary medicine.
This was partially due to my younger brother, two years younger, dropped out of Tech
and went back and ran our ranch at south of Abilene.
Constable was married before I was, and I felt that the ranch was not large enough for two people to be managers.
So that's the reason I went up and got my master's.
no thought of it before that.
Had you started by using your husband's degree for county agent work or anything like that?
Well, I had written some letters and I didn't seem very excited about what was offered.
And this happened in my senior year.
I didn't have a very big gap.
They had
two previous doing the same project with sheep, something with their sheep.
And of course Dr. Stangle there at Texas Tech recommended me for it because I happened to be president of Block Bridal Club and I had raised and been on the cattle rights and sheep rights.
When did you finish Tech?
Boy.
That's all right.
I graduated up from North Dakota at 42, and two years there, so that would be 39 to 40.
Yeah, just so I can.
Yeah.
If you want me to drop back, or I can drop back on my childhood
earlier, I mean later.
Let's go on with this.
The sequence will be better for you, I believe.
While I was there, of course, the World War II broke out in December and I graduated in June or so of the following year.
And I had enlisted in the Marine Corps during my
senior during my second year and had written a thesis, written a paper and a thesis and the Marine Corps called me in before graduation time.
The faculty was very sympathetic
gave me my exam and accepted this work that I'd already done as my thesis.
But I'm lucky.
You are.
Anyway, I went into the service about March, April of 42 and was a, went into the Marine Officer School and came out a second lieutenant, a Marine,
I don't think that has a lot to do with veterinary medicine.
I went to Honolulu and then joined a defense battalion that was in Palmyra, one of the islands that was the next one to be invaded.
I remember not so good.
You had a small stroke on .
Yeah, no, before that.
Anyway, before, when we turned them around.
Yeah.
was the next .
And I was there a short while, and then came back and changed into a field cartel.
I had lots of, quite a bit of math, and the Marine Corps tried to use your word.
best fitted, and that certainly saved me a lot of walking.
Vietnam, I'd have been in Vietnam, not Vietnam, but Guadalcanal.
My outfit would have gone to Guadalcanal if I'd been in anything but artillery or coastal artillery.
But anyway, I came back and then went out to Majuro on a different outfit.
there for a few months, and came, I was overseas 23 months, and came back to the United States.
Pacific all the time?
Yes, Pacific all the time.
And went back to Quantico to an advanced course, and then went back to San Francisco to be deployed again.
Funny thing that probably the
European war ended while I was going to Quantico, and the Japanese war ended while I was on the road to San Francisco, so I never went back.
I was lucky not to end up in the occupation.
Okay, from there I...
When did you leave service?
about December 4th, 6th, and I applied for application to three veterinary schools, Cornell and...
So you had kind of decided during the war what you wanted to come back and do.
Yes, that made up my mind.
My brother was running the ranch until he went into the service, and then of course he came back about the same time I did.
Went back to the ranch.
So I figured that would be the best way to go.
Cornell and Colorado and A&M.
A&M accepted more of my previous college work than the other two.
And therefore, I really would have liked to have gone to Cornell.
But I thought it was a better school.
It rated better.
Yeah, it did.
It was an honor.
But that's not for the book.
But anyway, I went to A&M, the veterinary school, in January, I believe, mid-semester of 46, and graduated in 49.
I hit some of the, most of the, I don't know, three-year schedule at that time.
at least a high sophomore.
All my English and most of my chemistry and all that was done in history.
But I graduated in 49 from A&M.
You were with GI Bill.
Yes, uh-huh.
And I taught in the animal husbandry.
I was married at that time.
I didn't know I asked the other.
Yeah, I was married and had two children during that time.
So I had to have a little bit more than you have to be able to get through.
So I taught in the animal husbandry, mostly dealing with the judging team, stock doings, and telemetry, animal husbandry.
Do you remember anything special about any of your professors down there when you were there, or any special professors?
Well, we had a few characters, but Dr. Turk was a fellow of parasitology.
My name is Turk.
Did you know Tom, my name, while you were there?
No.
What year did he graduate?
About the same time.
I was going to look at his degree.
He was 47.
So he's down to 47.
I crisscrossed with some of the 48s, but not 47.
Anyway, Dr. Turk and, oh, who was the...
I think Marcel is still around.
Yes, he was our dean.
And Dr. Smith.
Yeah, he was the head of the physiology department.
I'll think of him in a minute.
I have a small stroke.
a few years back, and I have trouble on recall.
I can think of it.
It's fine.
But if I try to think of it, it just won't come.
And the anatomy teacher, a tall fellow, blond, very instrumental.
I enjoyed him.
Of course, a few of you didn't enjoy him.
Now was the emphasis you felt like when you were there a large animal?
Oh yeah, definitely.
You didn't have much... No, you couldn't get in if you wanted to be a small animal.
I intended to be a large animal too with my agricultural background.
It was easy to do that.
So you finished in 49 and then what did you do?
I looked around for various places to practice and I ended up in Longview, Texas.
setting up a mixed practice.
By yourself?
Yes, new practice.
And how'd that work?
It worked fine.
I had all I could do and was at the point of having to hire another veterinarian when I decided that maybe I'd sell and come to West Texas.
We were, my wife's in North Dakota and
I was West Texas, and East Texas is different.
I was very successful there and sold my practice.
Had it on the market three days.
Is that right?
Yeah.
Now you had an edge, it strikes me, maybe on some of these other people, because you had a lot of economics background.
You bet I did.
I made all of that.
And you know, this is a question I ask all these people.
What was your business?
Because I see the practice of veterinary medicine as a business.
Oh, it is.
And apparently that's one of the real deficiencies that a lot of these people have had.
Well, I ended up with four.
I'm going to tear this thing up here.
I had four hospitals here, and that helped me on that.
I branched out, and I had a partnership and so forth.
But when I sold those, that's my retirement.
And it's...
And so that's the economics part of it.
That's important.
And I raised that question with Calvin Price and several people, you know, and apparently the curriculum...
I had Texas Tech, too.
I had a good... That was one reason I asked for it up there.
And the curriculum just doesn't have room, apparently, for anything like that.
I think that's a real one.
Oh, it's where a big lot of them...
their education, I think.
So how long were you in Longview?
About two years, probably two years.
So you set up a practice that you could actually sell in two years.
That's pretty good.
Yeah, yeah.
That's pretty good.
I didn't ask enough because it sold too quick, but it sold to a fella in Kilgore that had a practice over there and knew, he grew up in Longview, in Marshall, so he knew the area.
We were good friends.
I looked around and tried to go into Dallas.
And you saw without knowing where you were going?
No, that's right.
You were very brave.
Well, hard-headed maybe.
But anyway, Dallas was nearly a closed city as far as building veterinary hospitals.
You had to find some county land inside Dallas
to get the zoning right to build a hospital.
And so I looked at court work, which really I loved more than I did Dallas, but thought there was more opportunity over there.
And found out that they'd had a new zoning rule that allowed you to go into areas that you couldn't go into otherwise.
Now, has this been a continual problem for the practice, that is, your zoning problem?
See, we are criticized for noise, barking, and for odors.
It's been a real problem down through the years.
And St. Louis formed a, not a resolution, a law, a zoning law,
formed a new zoning law that allowed the veterinarians to go in with pretty much a closed building.
And that made all the difference in the world.
Because you were accepted, if you followed that one, two or three zones that you couldn't have gone in otherwise.
And you could go in residential areas that are close to residential areas, which you needed to be.
Has that been pretty well adopted now?
Yeah, so it's universal.
But it came out of St. Louis?
Yes, and it came out about 51, 52, about 52, 53, something like that.
Most everybody knows that.
There was one guy named Bill.
Two hospitals in Fort Worth just before I came and couldn't move in them, built them.
And I thought he would qualify, and then the city adopted that building along, and I was able to do what I wanted to.
So you come on over to Fort Worth?
Yes, and I worked in Dallas.
And then you go to the hospital right away?
I worked in Dallas for about three months, but then I built my hospital and my home.
on the west side of Ridgely area.
And you're probably unique again, and you've got capital to start out with.
Well, I used my ranch to... You got some credit.
...as equity.
My father died when I was 12.
I need to go back and cover that somewhere, but a man, when we became of age, my mother deeded his part to us of the ranch, which was in Memphis.
case, a section, and I used it for financing over and over again with Southwestern Life as a loan on it, and take that money and invest it in the hospital.
And it's been very, very good for me.
But I think, and I had an uncle who loaned me $10,000.
So by the time I was building a house and everything, I didn't have enough.
Never, never.
You need an uncle or a grandfather or a father that finances you.
And you're unique in that.
And you're unique that, I want you to make this point, that we have something to sell when we retire.
We're not like dentists and particularly MDs.
They have a lot of trouble.
selling their establishment, MDs, selling their practice.
And we have the practice plus physical building and income coming in, which is tougher at the beginning, but it's better at the retirement.
Most of them, a lot of them haven't even thought about that.
Yeah, I picked up on that from a number of people.
You have to provide your own retirement in our family.
Your social security is just a drop in the bucket.
Let me go back and pick up a child.
Yeah, go ahead, because your father died when you were young, and your mother is running the ranch.
Yeah.
My father died when I was 12.
And I was the oldest child of five children.
And she ran the ranch, living in Merkle, with the ranch 35 miles south of there.
We had a very good foreman who continued for several years.
And then we had another very good man who was a foreman.
And we had advice from my uncle, who was a rancher, to help him.
I would work at the ranch every summer.
We moved out there.
You were staying in Miracle, so you'd go to school?
Go to school, that's right.
So I would have a decent education.
My mother was a graduate of Hardin-Simmons, so she appreciated an education and desired that we all have one.
As a brother, we all did get degrees.
That was good for me in lots of respects and made a very serious upbringing for a boy.
I don't think I had to act as kind of her right hand.
And also, I miss all the summer activities that kids have in town, like bicycling, swimming, things like that.
But I think it was good education.
So when you, this goes, when you go off to school, your brother had decided he wants to be a rancher.
That seems to be the way.
We both went to Tech.
I was there a year before he came.
He was two years younger.
It just wasn't for him.
He was never, didn't make excellent grades.
He was as sharp as a tack, but he just didn't go to school.
And he married early, and it was a natural thing to go to the ranch.
Did he stay with the ranch?
Yes.
He died when he was 51.
We all have heart problems, seriously, I mean.
His wife is running the ranch right now.
Is that right?
Yeah.
So we leased our property to her, and she runs it that way.
I was the second president of the Tarrant County Veterinary Medical Association here, and a classmate of mine
was the first president.
Who was that?
Oh, gosh, you remember?
That's all right.
I'm sure I've got that.
I think I've probably got that.
Out of Houston.
I think I've got that in Tarrant.
The Tarrant County history are a little off.
Anyway, what was the attitude of people?
When you started in practice here, I would imagine Fort Worth would be really strongly supportive of veterinary medicine.
period and don't understand it pretty much.
Not particularly.
They had had an association for a very short time, maybe two or three years way back.
And then my classmates, I think five of us, came here.
And we just decided that we needed one.
And my wife decided to try and organize the women.
And she got the damnedest bawling out and reading down you ever saw from one of the older veterinarians' wives.
Not much older, but it ended up this gal was the third wife's veterinary president.
She switched her tune and came in.
But that's another story.
But I think you had one of the better state
I was president of it twice.
We ran down and we decided for about three or four years we'd re-run some presidents and get it going again.
Do you happen to remember when you were first served as president and when you were last president what the number of members were?
Or how many practitioners there were?
15 years difference there.
I know the first meeting I met in the hospital, the organizational meeting, and I would say it was 15, 20 members.
And I was supposed to give some of this to
Dr. Farrell's wife, she was doing the write-ups of Tarrant County information.
I have a different file on it, but I didn't bring it today.
I'll get that from you later, Farrell.
Yeah.
I missed something back there I wanted to tell you.
With the ranch?
Yeah, I've got that time.
My wife and I were both presidents of the TVMA.
at the same time.
And that was in 62.
And that was the first time that happened.
Let me give you a little bit of TVMA stuff.
Yeah, I sure do.
These are extra coffees.
You're welcome to them.
And all of them deal with my time except that top one.
And it tells, one article in there tells about Dan being elected the national president.
National office.
Good.
Yeah, I appreciate that.
You want these back?
No, I have copies.
All right.
Thank you.
I have one or two.
Yeah, that's really handy.
One or two that I don't want to give up.
No, no, don't do that.
Let me start back this again.
That's great.
I had one real controversial thing happen when I was president.
We'll talk about it at last.
And you might just mention the names or what names.
It doesn't matter.
It's over and the man's dead on that.
My regime, we started the first seminars being held out in the state.
OK.
It's a continuing education program.
The first one was held in Arlington.
Why did you do that?
What was the situation?
Well, we felt the need for it that other than the state convention and the seminar
It was held in June at College Station, where the only educational, continuing education, particularly that of the veterinarian, could attend.
And we figured that if you brought subjects that weren't approached at these meetings and made them so that veterinarians did not have to travel over 50, 60 miles, we would keep her.
up to date and that's been a very big bug with me.
I am one of the early people in Texas in the American Animal Hospital Association and that's our theme is continuing education and keeping up to date.
Now, were the state conventions seen or used at all as a mechanism for being informed, do you think, before this time?
Oh, yeah.
They had programs, yeah.
This is a program.
Of course, it had a lot of my friends in it.
These are the conventions.
I can loan you this.
No, I've got those in Austin.
Don't give me anything that you don't have.
Oh, here's the problem.
It's quite educational.
But it was relied on as a mechanism for trying to maintain some degree of the room.
And it moved from Fort Worth, Dallas, Houston, and San Antonio primarily.
It was real unusual to
go anywhere else.
And when was the state, I interviewed Charlie Huff, when was the state offices moved to Austin?
Right here.
Okay.
That's what I was thinking.
No, wait a minute.
We may have moved just in Austin.
Yeah, because that's okay.
I was just trying to associate it with your involvement, if there was any association.
Now, who was the executive secretary, I guess, of the association when you were
When I was, it was King from Dallas.
He was a, Paul King, he was a CPR man.
Was hired three years earlier, two years earlier, at an Abilene convention.
Glenn Savage succeeded him during my regime.
Glenn Savage, we advertised in the four main newspapers, San Antonio, Houston, well, Austin, too.
for an executive secretary and told them what we wanted.
And the board of directors interviewed 53 persons in Austin.
And you don't need to put this in if you want to.
It's an interesting thing.
We had had a brother of a governor apply.
A fellow had run for the
Attorney General Lopi, a PR man that had been a San Antonio for years, PR man from Denver, and Glenn Savage, who was executive secretary for ICCRD, representing from Wichita Falls.
At that time?
He was the executive secretary, Akard, Akard, I-K-A-R-D. Well, funny thing, he called me up at about 10, 11 o'clock on the last Sunday that we were interviewing and said he'd only heard about it.
We didn't have any paper on him, you know, background, history, anything.
But he sounded so good that I...
told him, come on down, and we'd interview him.
And I took it on myself.
And at 3.30 or so in the afternoon, he was bailing hay at the time.
And he left out, came on down.
And he was so much what we wanted that he sold himself on us.
And he had a tremendous opposition in the people we had interviewed.
Very good people.
Well, let me ask, what were you looking for, and was there a special need you had?
We wanted somebody that, it sounds silly, but could write letters, get us good publicity.
We felt that his background there was very good.
Hackard was head of the oil committees and very successful in the national representative in the House.

uh and he uh didn't know boots about veterinary medicine but he was very interested in it he had a partial farm background uh i would say it was his uh his education and his uh employment that caused us to hire him and enthusiasm he was uh and he was uh an executive secretary for
About five years, approximately.
He went out when the Valley came in.
He was not in Norton's regime.
But he really did a lot for our association.
What did he do?
And again, what did you want him to do?
Well, for one thing, we
were under the state sales tax.
And he and Bob Dillons up in the managed, excuse me, Bob were the main.
He was very active in .
Jones, Bob Jones, in getting veterinarians out from under the sales tax.
We had it for about two years.
And most veterinarians had to pay it, but didn't charge for it.
So we were absorbing it ourselves.
And I give Bob Jones, who was our legislative chairman, that credit.
Second thing, we increased the membership greatly.
I don't have that figure.
How'd you do that?
Well, it was hard going.
Did you sell it at school?
At school we didn't get anywhere.
We tried to, but most of the members, our teachers wouldn't even be members.
I've heard that's no problem.
The anatomy teacher there is one.
that talked me down to the very, he said, well, he wasn't even, didn't even take the state board.
He wasn't licensed in Texas.
A bunch of them, by the way.
They were hard heads.
And Jones, you can give him credit for breaking that barrier.
I talked to Al Price, who was my classmate, became dean at a San Antonio meeting.
And I said, Al, it doesn't look very good when less than 50% of the faculty, and it was quite a bit less, about 30,000, can't be members of your state association.
And during my regime or the next one, I believe it was the next one, there came up a deal where they were raising salaries all over Texas
university people.
And A&M would not have gotten raises had not our profession been all out.
And I told Al that.
And he went back and made changes.
He didn't issue an edict, but it was damn close to an edict.
And I don't know if there's nothing else you might
That's something those people still need to be reminded of.
You know that?
It's amazing how faculty just can't get in their minds.
My first article there is that, is trying to tell veterinarians what we did for them.
And faculty just can't get in their minds that they have obligations.
The military, the same way.
They, a lot, we had very few military members.
But they need to be a member of the local association and the state because, besides the national one,
But we instigated seminars.
That was another thing.
Let me see.
Sales tax.
Oh, we broke the Dallas-Fort Worth-Houston routine and sent the convention to
I think in Monterey.
The Valley.
Just a minute.
I had our first one there in quite a while.
The Valley had a very good veterinary group and had been asking and asking and asking to have an association.
This thing happened at Amarillo and El Paso in later years.
and the Corpus Christi one, but those are about the only times it's missed the big city, but for the state convention.
I missed it.
Brownville.
Brownville, yes.
Every association goes through it, and Texas goes through it.
You bet.
Probably.
AHA and AVMA go through the same thing.
Yeah.
I'm sure you've got to see that over and over.
We had a liaison with the
Texas Pharmacy group, just as we were.
The TVMA, they were there.
They were pharmaceutical and worked out a lot of drug problems or drug reviews sold in pharmacies.
They really had veneer labels.
And that was one thing we started, and it ensued through the years.
But it was the first thing that resonated there.
Where did Savage go when he left to get your man?
He became a manager and partial owner for a veterinary sales group that Bob Jones headed.
And it was up in the South Plains for about three, four years.
And then he bought out our farm, Lone Star, got their supply here in Fort Worth.
So he's still in there?
In that, yes.
But I thought that our hiring might make a good little side story.
Yeah, that is.
Here's Dan.
You have this book.
Yeah.
And it also brings that new office.
And that's in the book there, too.
Good.
So in your practice, let's go back to your practice now.
You start out with a hospital, you go to your hospital, and you're still doing a mixed practice, basically.
Yes, for a few years.
I would say five to seven years, something like that, I was in mixed practice.
And then what happened?
Well, primarily the dairies and horse, people that had horses and stuff were zoned out to
a radius of over 10 miles, and it was inconvenient to leave an office full of people and go out and make a large animal call.
The economics were not good, and the sentiment in the hospital was not good.
Even if you had two people in the hospital, which I did pretty early,
It still wasn't a paying thing.
Most of them may fall this way.
It's the economics of it.
Sure.
You can't leave a steady income where you got your investment to go out on a $10, $15 horse call.
Now, were the small animal clients intruding on you anyway?
In other words, they're coming?
No.
I set up to...
I learned in Longview that they were there and they were ready to come to anybody.
I learned a lot there and I learned in working for this veteran in Dallas what a good hospital it was.
When you were in school, did you have any kind of specifications for what went into an animal hospital?
No.
After I got out, AVMA, AAHA, American Animal Hospital Association, published a small book on it, and that's the first thing.
Then they got the sponsoring hospital of the month,
which in their publication showed his hospital plan, how he financed it, and his building.
And it became several firms in the United States, three or four, that had more knowledge than all the others.
And they came to the forefront and improved hospital design.
American Animal Hospital bears the burden of teaching
that the schools did not.
And while in school, I visited as many hospitals as I could and drew their floor plans.
And I have built one, two, three, four hospitals and bought one other one.
Were you operating them all at one time?
No, I operated those in partial business with four of them.
Partnerships.
But I think that I've been through greatly.
Each plan was better than the previous one.
And also, I built mine to be able to build onto
tried to build the others that way that the additions would not ruin the looks of it and ruin the efficiency of it.
And that's a hard thing to accomplish.
Yeah, yeah.
Now when you move into your, more and more into small animal, did you finally make a decision that that's the way you're going to go?
Yes, definitely.
Yeah, I sold all my instruments or gave them away.
I made

One call about three or four years later, a good friend of mine, when we'd go out and check a horse for a Christmas wedding, a good old gentle horse, and it was in December, of course, and pretty frosty.
